{"nodes":[{"pos":[17,240],"content":"We introduce the XAML language and XAML concepts to the Windows Runtime app developer audience, and describe the different ways to declare objects and set attributes in XAML as it is used for creating a Windows Runtime app.","needQuote":true,"needEscape":true,"nodes":[{"content":"We introduce the XAML language and XAML concepts to the Windows Runtime app developer audience, and describe the different ways to declare objects and set attributes in XAML as it is used for creating a Windows Runtime app.","pos":[0,223]}]},{"pos":[248,261],"content":"XAML overview","needQuote":true,"needEscape":true,"nodes":[{"content":"XAML overview","pos":[0,13]}]},{"content":"XAML overview","pos":[318,331]},{"content":"\\[ Updated for UWP apps on Windows 10.","pos":[333,371]},{"content":"For Windows 8.x articles, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>archive<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132)</ept> \\]","pos":[372,467],"source":" For Windows 8.x articles, see the [archive](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132) \\]"},{"content":"We introduce the XAML language and XAML concepts to the Windows Runtime app developer audience, and describe the different ways to declare objects and set attributes in XAML as it is used for creating a Windows Runtime app.","pos":[469,692]},{"content":"What is XAML?","pos":[697,710]},{"content":"Extensible Application Markup Language (XAML) is a declarative language.","pos":[712,784]},{"content":"Specifically, XAML can initialize objects and set properties of objects, using a language structure that shows hierarchical relationships between multiple objects, and using a backing type convention that supports extension of types.","pos":[785,1018]},{"content":"You can create visible UI elements in the declarative XAML markup.","pos":[1019,1085]},{"content":"You can then associate a separate code-behind file for each XAML file that can respond to events and manipulate the objects that you originally declare in XAML.","pos":[1086,1246]},{"content":"The XAML language supports interchange of sources between different tools and roles in the development process, such as exchanging XAML sources between design tools and an IDE, or between primary developers and localization developers.","pos":[1248,1483]},{"content":"By using XAML as the interchange format, designer roles and developer roles can be kept separate or brought together, and designers and developers can iterate during the production of an app.","pos":[1484,1675]},{"content":"When you see them as part of your Windows Runtime app projects, XAML files are XML files with the .xaml file name extension.","pos":[1677,1801]},{"content":"Basic XAML syntax","pos":[1806,1823]},{"content":"XAML has a basic syntax that builds on XML.","pos":[1825,1868]},{"content":"By definition, valid XAML must also be valid XML.","pos":[1869,1918]},{"content":"But XAML also has syntax concepts that are assigned a different and more complete meaning, while still being valid in XML per the XML 1.0 specification.","pos":[1919,2071]},{"content":"For example, XAML supports <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>property element syntax<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, where property values can be set within elements rather than as string values in attributes or as content.","pos":[2072,2232],"source":" For example, XAML supports *property element syntax*, where property values can be set within elements rather than as string values in attributes or as content."},{"content":"To regular XML, a XAML property element is an element with a dot in its name, so it's valid to plain XML but doesn't have the same meaning.","pos":[2233,2372]},{"content":"XAML and Microsoft Visual Studio","pos":[2377,2409]},{"content":"Microsoft Visual Studio helps you to produce valid XAML syntax, both in the XAML text editor and in the more graphically oriented XAML design surface.","pos":[2411,2561]},{"content":"So when you write XAML for your app using Visual Studio, don't worry too much about the syntax with each keystroke.","pos":[2562,2677]},{"content":"The IDE encourages valid XAML syntax by providing autocompletion hints, showing suggestions in Microsoft IntelliSense lists and dropdowns, showing UI element libraries in the toolbox, or other techniques.","pos":[2678,2882]},{"content":"If this is your first experience with XAML, it might still be useful to know the syntax rules and particularly the terminology that is sometimes used to describe the restrictions or choices when we describe XAML syntax in reference or other topics.","pos":[2883,3131]},{"content":"We cover these fine points of XAML syntax in a separate topic, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAML syntax guide<ept id=\"p1\">](xaml-syntax-guide.md)</ept>.","pos":[3132,3237],"source":" We cover these fine points of XAML syntax in a separate topic, [XAML syntax guide](xaml-syntax-guide.md)."},{"content":"XAML namespaces","pos":[3242,3257]},{"content":"In general programming, a namespace is an organizing concept that determines how identifiers for programming entities are interpreted.","pos":[3259,3393]},{"content":"By using namespaces, a programming framework can separate user-declared identifiers from framework-declared identifiers, disambiguate identifiers through namespace qualifications, enforce rules for scoping names, and so on.","pos":[3394,3617]},{"content":"XAML has its own XAML namespace concept that serves this purpose for the XAML language.","pos":[3618,3705]},{"content":"Here's how XAML applies and extends the XML language namespace concepts:","pos":[3706,3778]},{"content":"XAML uses the reserved XML attribute <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>xmlns<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> for namespace declarations.","pos":[3784,3858],"source":"XAML uses the reserved XML attribute **xmlns** for namespace declarations."},{"content":"The value of the attribute is typically a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), which is a convention inherited from XML.","pos":[3859,3977]},{"content":"XAML uses prefixes in declarations to declare non-default namespaces, and prefix usages in elements and attributes reference that namespace.","pos":[3982,4122]},{"content":"XAML has a concept of a default namespace, which is the namespace used when no prefix exists in a usage or declaration.","pos":[4127,4246]},{"content":"The default namespace can be defined differently for each XAML programming framework.","pos":[4247,4332]},{"content":"Namespace definitions inherit in a XAML file or construct, from parent element to child element.","pos":[4337,4433]},{"content":"For example if you define a namespace in the root element of a XAML file, all elements within that file inherit that namespace definition.","pos":[4434,4572]},{"content":"If an element further into the page redefines the namespace, that element's descendants inherit the new definition.","pos":[4573,4688]},{"content":"Attributes of an element inherit the element's namespaces.","pos":[4693,4751]},{"content":"It's fairly uncommon to see prefixes on XAML attributes.","pos":[4752,4808]},{"content":"A XAML file almost always declares a default XAML namespace in its root element.","pos":[4810,4890]},{"content":"The default XAML namespace defines which elements you can declare without qualifying them by a prefix.","pos":[4891,4993]},{"content":"For typical Windows Runtime app projects, this default namespace contains all the built-in XAML vocabulary for the Windows Runtime that's used for UI definitions: the default controls, text elements, XAML graphics and animations, databinding and styling support types, and so on.","pos":[4994,5273]},{"content":"Most of the XAML you'll write for Windows Runtime apps will thus be able to avoid using XAML namespaces and prefixes when referring to common UI elements.","pos":[5274,5428]},{"content":"Here's a snippet showing a template-created <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Page<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227503)</ept> root of the initial page for an app (showing the opening tag only, and simplified).","pos":[5430,5626],"source":"Here's a snippet showing a template-created [**Page**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br227503) root of the initial page for an app (showing the opening tag only, and simplified)."},{"content":"It declares the default namespace and also the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>x<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> namespace (which we'll explain next).","pos":[5627,5717],"source":" It declares the default namespace and also the **x** namespace (which we'll explain next)."},{"content":"The XAML-language XAML namespace","pos":[5909,5941]},{"content":"One particular XAML namespace that is declared in nearly every Windows Runtime XAML file is the XAML-language namespace.","pos":[5943,6063]},{"content":"This namespace includes elements and concepts that are defined by the XAML language, by its language specification.","pos":[6064,6179]},{"content":"By convention, the XAML-language XAML namespace is mapped to the prefix \"x\".","pos":[6180,6256]},{"content":"The default project and file templates for Windows Runtime app projects always define both the default XAML namespace (no prefix, just <ph id=\"ph1\">`xmlns=`</ph>) and the XAML-language XAML namespace (prefix \"x\") as part of the root element.","pos":[6257,6480],"source":" The default project and file templates for Windows Runtime app projects always define both the default XAML namespace (no prefix, just `xmlns=`) and the XAML-language XAML namespace (prefix \"x\") as part of the root element."},{"content":"The \"x\" prefix/XAML-language XAML namespace contains several programming constructs that you use often in your XAML.","pos":[6482,6598]},{"content":"Here are the most common ones:","pos":[6599,6629]},{"content":"Term","pos":[6633,6637]},{"content":"Description","pos":[6640,6651]},{"content":"x:Key","pos":[6680,6685]},{"content":"Sets a unique user-defined key for each resource in a XAML <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ResourceDictionary<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208794)</ept>.","pos":[6709,6851],"source":"Sets a unique user-defined key for each resource in a XAML [**ResourceDictionary**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208794)."},{"content":"The key's token string is the argument for the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>StaticResource<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> markup extension, and you use this key later to retrieve the XAML resource from another XAML usage elsewhere in your app's XAML.","pos":[6852,7046],"source":" The key's token string is the argument for the **StaticResource** markup extension, and you use this key later to retrieve the XAML resource from another XAML usage elsewhere in your app's XAML."},{"content":"x:Class","pos":[7052,7059]},{"content":"Specifies the code namespace and code class name for the class that provides code-behind for a XAML page.","pos":[7085,7190]},{"content":"This names the class that is created or joined by the build actions when you build your app.","pos":[7191,7283]},{"content":"These build actions support the XAML markup compiler and combine your markup and code-behind when the app is compiled.","pos":[7284,7402]},{"content":"You must have such a class to support code-behind for a XAML page.","pos":[7403,7469]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Window.Content<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209051)</ept> in the default Windows Runtime activation model.","pos":[7470,7597],"source":"[**Window.Content**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209051) in the default Windows Runtime activation model."},{"content":"x:Name","pos":[7603,7609]},{"content":"Specifies a run-time object name for the instance that exists in run-time code after an object element defined in XAML is processed.","pos":[7634,7766]},{"content":"You can think of setting <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>x:Name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> in XAML as being like declaring a named variable in code.","pos":[7767,7860],"source":" You can think of setting **x:Name** in XAML as being like declaring a named variable in code."},{"content":"As you'll learn later, that's exactly what happens when your XAML is loaded as a component of a Windows Runtime app.","pos":[7861,7977]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>FrameworkElement.Name<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208735)</ept> is a similar property in the framework but not all elements support it.","pos":[8002,8169],"source":"**Note**  [**FrameworkElement.Name**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208735) is a similar property in the framework but not all elements support it."},{"content":"So you use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>x:Name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> for element identification, whenever <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>FrameworkElement.Name<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> is not supported on that element type.","pos":[8170,8293],"source":" So you use **x:Name** for element identification, whenever **FrameworkElement.Name** is not supported on that element type."},{"content":"x:Uid","pos":[8299,8304]},{"content":"Identifies elements that should use localized resources for some of their property values.","pos":[8328,8418]},{"content":"For more info on how to use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>x:Uid<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, see <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Quickstart: Translating UI resources<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/hh965329)</ept>.","pos":[8419,8564],"source":" For more info on how to use **x:Uid**, see [Quickstart: Translating UI resources](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/hh965329)."},{"content":"XAML intrinsic data types","pos":[8570,8595]},{"content":"These types can specify values for simple value-types when that's required for an attribute or resource.","pos":[8629,8733]},{"content":"These intrinsic types correspond to the simple value types that are typically defined as part of each programming language's intrinsic definitions.","pos":[8734,8881]},{"content":"For example, you might need an object representing a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>true<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Boolean value to use in an <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>ObjectAnimationUsingKeyFrames<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br210320)</ept> storyboarded visual state.","pos":[8882,9091],"source":" For example, you might need an object representing a **true** Boolean value to use in an [**ObjectAnimationUsingKeyFrames**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br210320) storyboarded visual state."},{"content":"For that value in XAML, you'd use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>x:Boolean<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> intrinsic type as the object element, like this:","pos":[9092,9192],"source":" For that value in XAML, you'd use the **x:Boolean** intrinsic type as the object element, like this: "},{"content":"Other programming constructs in the XAML-language XAML namespace exist but are not as common.","pos":[9250,9343]},{"content":"Mapping custom types to XAML namespaces","pos":[9348,9387]},{"content":"One of the most powerful aspects of XAML as a language is that it's easy to extend the XAML vocabulary for your Windows Runtime apps.","pos":[9389,9522]},{"content":"You can define your own custom types in your app's programming language and then reference your custom types in XAML markup.","pos":[9523,9647]},{"content":"Support for extension through custom types is fundamentally built-in to how the XAML language works.","pos":[9648,9748]},{"content":"Frameworks or app developers are responsible for creating the backing objects that XAML references.","pos":[9749,9848]},{"content":"Neither frameworks nor the app developer are bound by specifications of what the objects in their vocabularies represent or do beyond the basic XAML syntax rules (there are some expectations of what the XAML-language XAML namespace types should do, but the Windows Runtime provides all the necessary support).","pos":[9849,10158]},{"content":"If you use XAML for types that come from libraries other than the Windows Runtime core libraries and metadata, you must declare and map a XAML namespace with a prefix.","pos":[10160,10327]},{"content":"Use that prefix in element usages to reference the types that were defined in your library.","pos":[10328,10419]},{"content":"You declare prefix mappings as <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>xmlns<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> attributes, typically in a root element along with the other XAML namespace definitions.","pos":[10420,10549],"source":" You declare prefix mappings as **xmlns** attributes, typically in a root element along with the other XAML namespace definitions."},{"content":"To make your own namespace definition that references custom types, you first specify the keyword <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>xmlns:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, then the prefix you want.","pos":[10551,10686],"source":"To make your own namespace definition that references custom types, you first specify the keyword **xmlns:**, then the prefix you want."},{"content":"The value of that attribute must contain the keyword <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>using:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> as the first part of the value.","pos":[10687,10782],"source":" The value of that attribute must contain the keyword **using:** as the first part of the value."},{"content":"The remainder of the value is a string token that references the specific code-backing namespace that contains your custom types, by name.","pos":[10783,10921]},{"content":"The prefix defines the markup token that is used to refer to that XAML namespace in the remainder of the markup in that XAML file.","pos":[10923,11053]},{"content":"A colon character (:) goes between the prefix and the entity to be referenced within the XAML namespace.","pos":[11054,11158]},{"pos":[11160,11346],"content":"For example, the attribute syntax to map a prefix <ph id=\"ph1\">`myTypes`</ph> to the namespace <ph id=\"ph2\">`myCompany.myTypes`</ph> is: <ph id=\"ph3\">`    xmlns:myTypes=\"using:myCompany.myTypes\"`</ph>, and a representative element usage is:","source":"For example, the attribute syntax to map a prefix `myTypes` to the namespace `myCompany.myTypes` is: `    xmlns:myTypes=\"using:myCompany.myTypes\"`, and a representative element usage is: "},{"pos":[11374,11598],"content":"For more info on mapping XAML namespaces for custom types, including special considerations for Visual C++ component extensions (C++/CX), see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAML namespaces and namespace mapping<ept id=\"p1\">](xaml-namespaces-and-namespace-mapping.md)</ept>.","source":"For more info on mapping XAML namespaces for custom types, including special considerations for Visual C++ component extensions (C++/CX), see [XAML namespaces and namespace mapping](xaml-namespaces-and-namespace-mapping.md)."},{"content":"Other XAML namespaces","pos":[11603,11624]},{"content":"You often see XAML files that define the prefixes \"d\" (for designer namespace) and \"mc\" (for markup compatibility).","pos":[11626,11741]},{"content":"Generally these are for infrastructure support, or to enable scenarios in a design-time tool.","pos":[11742,11835]},{"content":"For more info, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>\"Other XAML namespaces\" section of the XAML namespaces topic<ept id=\"p1\">](xaml-namespaces-and-namespace-mapping.md#other-XAML-namespaces)</ept>.","pos":[11836,11986],"source":" For more info, see the [\"Other XAML namespaces\" section of the XAML namespaces topic](xaml-namespaces-and-namespace-mapping.md#other-XAML-namespaces)."},{"content":"Markup extensions","pos":[11991,12008]},{"content":"Markup extensions are a XAML language concept that is often used in the Windows Runtime XAML implementation.","pos":[12010,12118]},{"content":"Markup extensions often represent some kind of \"shortcut\" that enables a XAML file to access a value or behavior that isn't simply declaring elements based on backing types.","pos":[12119,12292]},{"content":"Some markup extensions can set properties with plain strings or with additionally nested elements, with the goal of streamlining the syntax or the factoring between different XAML files.","pos":[12293,12479]},{"content":"In XAML attribute syntax, curly braces \"{\" and \"}\" indicate a XAML markup extension usage.","pos":[12481,12571]},{"content":"This usage directs the XAML processing to escape from the general treatment of treating attribute values as either a literal string or a directly string-convertible value.","pos":[12572,12743]},{"content":"Instead, a XAML parser calls code that provides behavior for that particular markup extension, and that code provides an alternate object or behavior result that the XAML parser needs.","pos":[12744,12928]},{"content":"Markup extensions can have arguments, which follow the markup extension name and are also contained within the curly braces.","pos":[12929,13053]},{"content":"Typically, an evaluated markup extension provides an object return value.","pos":[13054,13127]},{"content":"During parsing, that return value is inserted into the position in the object tree where the markup extension usage was in the source XAML.","pos":[13128,13267]},{"content":"Windows Runtime XAML supports these markup extensions that are defined under the default XAML namespace and are understood by the Windows Runtime XAML parser:","pos":[13269,13427]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>{xBind}<ept id=\"p1\">](x-bind-markup-extension.md)</ept>: supports data binding, which defers property evaluation until run-time by executing special-purpose code, which it generates at compile-time.","pos":[13433,13613],"source":"[{xBind}](x-bind-markup-extension.md): supports data binding, which defers property evaluation until run-time by executing special-purpose code, which it generates at compile-time."},{"cont