ut parsers ignore it."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>xml:space<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is valid, but is only relevant for scenarios described in the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>XAML and whitespace<ept id=\"p2\">](xaml-and-whitespace.md)</ept> topic.","pos":[22757,22885],"source":"**xml:space** is valid, but is only relevant for scenarios described in the [XAML and whitespace](xaml-and-whitespace.md) topic."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>encoding<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> attribute is valid in XAML.","pos":[22886,22930],"source":" The **encoding** attribute is valid in XAML."},{"content":"Only UTF-8 and UTF-16 encodings are supported.","pos":[22931,22977]},{"content":"UTF-32 encoding is not supported.","pos":[22978,23011]},{"content":"Case sensitivity in XAML","pos":[23018,23042]},{"content":"XAML is case-sensitive.","pos":[23044,23067]},{"content":"This is another consequence of XAML being based on XML, which is case-sensitive.","pos":[23068,23148]},{"content":"The names of XAML elements and attributes are case-sensitive.","pos":[23149,23210]},{"content":"The value of an attribute is potentially case-sensitive; this depends on how the attribute value is handled for particular properties.","pos":[23211,23345]},{"content":"For example, if the attribute value declares a member name of an enumeration, the built-in behavior that type-converts a member name string to return the enumeration member value is not case-sensitive.","pos":[23346,23547]},{"content":"In contrast, the value of the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property, and utility methods for working with objects based on the name that the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Name<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> property declares, treat the name string as case-sensitive.","pos":[23548,23737],"source":" In contrast, the value of the **Name** property, and utility methods for working with objects based on the name that the **Name** property declares, treat the name string as case-sensitive."},{"content":"XAML namescopes","pos":[23742,23757]},{"content":"The XAML language defines a concept of a XAML namescope.","pos":[23759,23815]},{"content":"The XAML namescope concept influences how XAML processors should treat the value of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>x:Name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> or <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Name<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> applied to XAML elements, particularly the scopes in which names should be relied upon to be unique identifiers.","pos":[23816,24035],"source":" The XAML namescope concept influences how XAML processors should treat the value of **x:Name** or **Name** applied to XAML elements, particularly the scopes in which names should be relied upon to be unique identifiers."},{"content":"XAML namescopes are covered in more detail in a separate topic; see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAML namescopes<ept id=\"p1\">](xaml-namescopes.md)</ept>.","pos":[24036,24142],"source":" XAML namescopes are covered in more detail in a separate topic; see [XAML namescopes](xaml-namescopes.md)."},{"content":"The role of XAML in the development process","pos":[24147,24190]},{"content":"XAML plays several important roles in the app development process.","pos":[24192,24258]},{"content":"XAML is the primary format for declaring an app's UI and elements in that UI, if you are programming using C#, Visual Basic or C++/CX.","pos":[24264,24398]},{"content":"Typically at least one XAML file in your project represents a page metaphor in your app for the initially displayed UI.","pos":[24399,24518]},{"content":"Additional XAML files might declare additional pages for navigation UI.","pos":[24519,24590]},{"content":"Other XAML files can declare resources, such as templates or styles.","pos":[24591,24659]},{"content":"You use the XAML format for declaring styles and templates applied to controls and UI for an app.","pos":[24664,24761]},{"content":"You might use styles and templates either for templating existing controls, or if you define a control that supplies a default template as part of a control package.","pos":[24766,24931]},{"content":"When you use it to define styles and templates, the relevant XAML is often declared as a discrete XAML file with a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ResourceDictionary<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208794)</ept> root.","pos":[24932,25135],"source":" When you use it to define styles and templates, the relevant XAML is often declared as a discrete XAML file with a [**ResourceDictionary**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208794) root."},{"content":"XAML is the common format for designer support of creating app UI and exchanging the UI design between different designer apps.","pos":[25140,25267]},{"content":"Most notably, XAML for the app can be interchanged between different XAML design tools (or design windows within tools).","pos":[25268,25388]},{"content":"Several other technologies also define the basic UI in XAML.","pos":[25393,25453]},{"content":"In relationship to Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) XAML and Microsoft Silverlight XAML, the XAML for Windows Runtime uses the same URI for its shared default XAML namespace.","pos":[25454,25633]},{"content":"The XAML vocabulary for Windows Runtime overlaps significantly with the XAML-for-UI vocabulary also used by Silverlight and to a slightly lesser extent by WPF.","pos":[25634,25793]},{"content":"Thus, XAML promotes an efficient migration pathway for UI originally defined for precursor technologies that also used XAML.","pos":[25794,25918]},{"content":"XAML defines the visual appearance of a UI, and an associated code-behind file defines the logic.","pos":[25923,26020]},{"content":"You can adjust the UI design without making changes to the logic in code-behind.","pos":[26021,26101]},{"content":"XAML simplifies the workflow between designers and developers.","pos":[26102,26164]},{"content":"Because of the richness of the visual designer and design surface support for the XAML language, XAML supports rapid UI prototyping in the early development phases.","pos":[26169,26333]},{"content":"Depending on your own role in the development process, you might not interact with XAML much.","pos":[26335,26428]},{"content":"The degree to which you do interact with XAML files also depends on which development environment you are using, whether you use interactive design environment features such as toolboxes and property editors, and the scope and purpose of your Windows Runtime app.","pos":[26429,26692]},{"content":"Nevertheless, it is likely that during development of the app, you will be editing a XAML file at the element level using a text or XML editor.","pos":[26693,26836]},{"content":"Using this info, you can confidently edit XAML in a text or XML representation and maintain the validity of that XAML file's declarations and purpose when it is consumed by tools, markup compile operations, or the run-time phase of your Windows Runtime app.","pos":[26837,27094]},{"content":"Optimize your XAML for load performance","pos":[27099,27138]},{"content":"Here are some tips for defining UI elements in XAML using best practices for performance.","pos":[27140,27229]},{"content":"Many of these tips relate to using XAML resources, but are listed here in the general XAML overview for convenience.","pos":[27230,27346]},{"content":"For more info about XAML resources see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ResourceDictionary and XAML resource references<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt187273)</ept>.","pos":[27347,27494],"source":" For more info about XAML resources see [ResourceDictionary and XAML resource references](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt187273)."},{"content":"For some more tips on performance, including XAML that purposely demonstrates some of the poor performance practices that you should avoid in your XAML, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Optimize your XAML markup<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt204779)</ept>.","pos":[27495,27738],"source":" For some more tips on performance, including XAML that purposely demonstrates some of the poor performance practices that you should avoid in your XAML, see [Optimize your XAML markup](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt204779)."},{"pos":[27744,27963],"content":"If you use the same color brush often in your XAML, define a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SolidColorBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242962)</ept> as a resource rather than using a named color as an attribute value each time.","source":"If you use the same color brush often in your XAML, define a [**SolidColorBrush**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242962) as a resource rather than using a named color as an attribute value each time."},{"content":"If you use the same resource on more than one UI page, consider defining it in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Application.Resources<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242338)</ept> rather than on each page.","pos":[27968,28158],"source":"If you use the same resource on more than one UI page, consider defining it in [**Application.Resources**](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242338) rather than on each page."},{"content":"Conversely, if only one page uses a resource, don't define it in <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Application.Resources<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and instead define it only for the page that needs it.","pos":[28159,28304],"source":" Conversely, if only one page uses a resource, don't define it in **Application.Resources** and instead define it only for the page that needs it."},{"content":"This is good both for XAML factoring while designing your app and for performance during XAML parsing.","pos":[28305,28407]},{"content":"For resources that your app packages, check for unused resources (a resource that has a k